WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.380 --> 00:00:07.410
Stargate, put that
name down in your books

00:00:07.410 --> 00:00:09.120
'cause I think you're
gonna hear a lot about

00:00:09.120 --> 00:00:10.170
it in the future.

00:00:10.170 --> 00:00:13.950
A new American company that
will invest $500 billion,

00:00:13.950 --> 00:00:17.010
at least in AI infrastructure. The

00:00:17.010 --> 00:00:19.050
data centers are actually
under construction.

00:00:19.050 --> 00:00:21.900
The first of them are under
construction in Texas.

00:00:21.900 --> 00:00:24.990
The Abilene location, which
is our first location,

00:00:24.990 --> 00:00:29.070
Abilene is a town on the
western central Plains of Texas.

00:00:29.070 --> 00:00:30.360
We kind of scratch

00:00:30.360 --> 00:00:32.070
and fight for everything
good that comes our way.

00:00:33.210 --> 00:00:34.260
I had people reaching out

00:00:34.260 --> 00:00:36.660
and they said, when is the
president gonna come see you?

00:00:36.660 --> 00:00:38.400
And I said, well, he
hasn't texted me yet so.

00:00:40.020 --> 00:00:41.400
I'm thrilled we get to do this in the

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:42.630
United States of America.

00:00:42.630 --> 00:00:45.300
I think this will be the most
important project of this era.

00:00:48.150 --> 00:00:50.490
Welcome to Abilene, Texas.

00:00:50.490 --> 00:00:53.760
This is the site of Project Stargate.

00:00:53.760 --> 00:00:56.040
A very mysterious, much talked about,

00:00:56.040 --> 00:00:59.580
much speculated about project
that brings together OpenAI,

00:00:59.580 --> 00:01:01.890
SoftBank, Oracle.

00:01:01.890 --> 00:01:03.810
If it all comes together building

00:01:03.810 --> 00:01:06.690
after building on this red
dirt behind me will be filled

00:01:06.690 --> 00:01:07.523
with chips that'll
power the AI revolution.

00:01:07.523 --> 00:01:08.356
What we're undergoing right now is sort

00:01:12.510 --> 00:01:15.270
of the largest infrastructure
build in human history.

00:01:15.270 --> 00:01:16.860
It's gonna create new
ways of doing business,

00:01:16.860 --> 00:01:18.630
it's gonna create new ways of invention

00:01:18.630 --> 00:01:20.850
and it's gonna really
drive humanity forward.

00:01:20.850 --> 00:01:22.110
I was in the real estate business.

00:01:22.110 --> 00:01:24.690
These buildings, these are
big, beautiful buildings,

00:01:24.690 --> 00:01:26.490
are gonna employ a lot of people.

00:01:26.490 --> 00:01:30.570
How do you personally grapple
with the pace of it all?

00:01:30.570 --> 00:01:32.910
It does feel like it's going very fast.

00:01:32.910 --> 00:01:35.760
I certainly think if I could
like transport myself back

00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:39.540
three years ago, it would seem
like unimaginable progress.

00:01:39.540 --> 00:01:44.490
This is amazing explosive
growth of intelligence

00:01:44.490 --> 00:01:46.740
that's coming in our decade.

00:01:46.740 --> 00:01:47.740
Everything will change.

00:01:49.080 --> 00:01:51.600
When Stargate was first
announced there was a

00:01:51.600 --> 00:01:52.710
lot of skepticism.

00:01:52.710 --> 00:01:55.650
A lot of people thought it's
just too big to be true.

00:01:55.650 --> 00:01:57.480
So this is your very first look.

00:02:04.740 --> 00:02:08.585
Hello. Hey Emily. Thank
you so much for having us.

00:02:08.585 --> 00:02:11.245
Welcome to Abilene. It's
so awesome to be here.

00:02:11.245 --> 00:02:12.960
Yeah, it's all happening.

00:02:12.960 --> 00:02:14.936
I know.
How many people are on this site

00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:18.510
Today we have about 2200 people on site.

00:02:20.490 --> 00:02:22.920
The guy at the heart of
the Stargate Build in Abilene

00:02:22.920 --> 00:02:24.750
is Chase Lochmiller.

00:02:24.750 --> 00:02:26.340
He's the founder of Crusoe,

00:02:26.340 --> 00:02:28.080
the little known data center startup,

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:30.210
overseeing this massive project.

00:02:30.210 --> 00:02:34.080
We started construction
here last June, June of 2024.

00:02:34.080 --> 00:02:37.867
This was just a com, a complete
barren field right? There was

00:02:37.867 --> 00:02:38.700
So there was nothing here in June.

00:02:38.700 --> 00:02:39.533
There were a bunch of mesquite
trees and bushes and brush.

00:02:42.900 --> 00:02:44.910
Stargate is so mysterious.

00:02:44.910 --> 00:02:45.743
What actually is happening here?

00:02:45.743 --> 00:02:46.576
What will eventually be here
is eight separate buildings

00:02:51.420 --> 00:02:53.455
all containing very large clusters

00:02:53.455 --> 00:02:55.440
of fully interconnected GPUs.

00:02:55.440 --> 00:02:57.630
Yep. We're gonna do a
tour of some of that.

00:02:58.930 --> 00:03:01.900
This is gonna get us around
that whole 1200 acre campus.

00:03:01.900 --> 00:03:03.580
Hey, we're going on an adventure.

00:03:03.580 --> 00:03:06.325
It's like getting around
Jurassic Park. I love that.

00:03:07.995 --> 00:03:10.450
Alright, let's go offroading. Yeah!

00:03:10.450 --> 00:03:11.283
I feel like we're going
on a data center safari.

00:03:11.283 --> 00:03:12.116
It is much like a data center safari

00:03:18.085 --> 00:03:19.930
Crusoe eight planned
buildings will hold up

00:03:19.930 --> 00:03:22.900
to 400,000 chips, which
would make this one

00:03:22.900 --> 00:03:25.840
of the world's largest
known compute clusters.

00:03:25.840 --> 00:03:28.870
The partners behind
Stargate, OpenAI, Oracle

00:03:28.870 --> 00:03:31.420
and SoftBank have committed
a hundred billion dollars

00:03:31.420 --> 00:03:32.980
to the project so far

00:03:32.980 --> 00:03:35.350
and claim they're prepared
to put in five times that

00:03:35.350 --> 00:03:37.630
as they expand to multiple sites.

00:03:37.630 --> 00:03:40.120
This first site in Abilene
has been dubbed Project

00:03:40.120 --> 00:03:41.915
Ludicrous as in

00:03:41.915 --> 00:03:42.915
Ludicrous speed.

00:03:44.500 --> 00:03:46.660
Ludicrous speed, which is appropriate.

00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:50.050
The whole thing is supposed
to be done by mid 2026.

00:03:50.050 --> 00:03:52.000
Are you round the clock? 24 hours a day?

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:53.470
We're, we're round the clock.

00:03:53.470 --> 00:03:55.900
It is very much a 24 7 operation.

00:03:55.900 --> 00:03:58.240
We're trying to deliver on,
you know, the fastest schedule

00:03:58.240 --> 00:04:00.040
that a a hundred megawatt or greater

00:04:00.040 --> 00:04:01.090
data center's ever been built.

00:04:02.410 --> 00:04:04.930
So why the ludicrous rush?

00:04:04.930 --> 00:04:08.380
Well, because Stargate is
part of a much larger AI race.

00:04:11.050 --> 00:04:14.440
Companies like Microsoft,
Meta, Google, Amazon,

00:04:14.440 --> 00:04:17.200
and xAI are all building AI data centers

00:04:17.200 --> 00:04:20.140
of their own at sites
across the US and beyond.

00:04:20.980 --> 00:04:24.430
Each company wants to have
the most capable AI being used

00:04:24.430 --> 00:04:25.690
by the most people

00:04:25.690 --> 00:04:27.190
and they've committed tens of billions

00:04:27.190 --> 00:04:28.480
of dollars to make it happen.

00:04:29.410 --> 00:04:31.420
There's no reason we won't
scale up our computing a

00:04:31.420 --> 00:04:33.220
hundred thousand times in a few years.

00:04:33.220 --> 00:04:34.960
I'm good for my 80 billion, right?

00:04:34.960 --> 00:04:38.180
I'm going to spend $80
billion building out Azure.

00:04:38.180 --> 00:04:40.810
The downside of being behind
is that you're out of position

00:04:40.810 --> 00:04:42.400
for like the most important technology

00:04:42.400 --> 00:04:44.080
for the next 10 to 15 years.

00:04:44.920 --> 00:04:48.220
But beyond just making better
AI, many tech leaders want

00:04:48.220 --> 00:04:51.340
to be the first to create AGI artificial

00:04:51.340 --> 00:04:52.840
general intelligence.

00:04:52.840 --> 00:04:54.640
A super smart agent that can think

00:04:54.640 --> 00:04:56.770
and learn just like a human if not better.

00:04:57.790 --> 00:05:00.340
Large language models like
ChatGPT have gotten more

00:05:00.340 --> 00:05:02.500
capable as the technology's evolved.

00:05:02.500 --> 00:05:04.900
So the hope is that adding
an astronomical amount

00:05:04.900 --> 00:05:07.090
of compute will make
them even more capable.

00:05:08.980 --> 00:05:10.090
Take me back to the beginning

00:05:10.090 --> 00:05:12.550
before Stargate, what
did you start seeing

00:05:12.550 --> 00:05:15.070
that made you realize
we need more compute,

00:05:15.070 --> 00:05:16.420
more power, more connectivity.

00:05:16.420 --> 00:05:17.380
Yeah,
That you were hitting a

00:05:17.380 --> 00:05:19.180
limit and needed to scale.

00:05:19.180 --> 00:05:20.710
We used to think a
lot about the compute.

00:05:20.710 --> 00:05:23.050
We would need to train the models

00:05:23.050 --> 00:05:26.440
and what we didn't use
to think about as much as

00:05:26.440 --> 00:05:28.510
how much people were
gonna use these models.

00:05:28.510 --> 00:05:30.190
And we did think about it, it
just turned out people want

00:05:30.190 --> 00:05:33.490
use the models much more than we imagined.

00:05:33.490 --> 00:05:36.340
And a couple of years ago, maybe

00:05:36.340 --> 00:05:37.173
after the launch of GPT 4

00:05:37.173 --> 00:05:38.006
in chatGPT,

00:05:39.220 --> 00:05:42.040
it really started to hit
like, oh man, this is,

00:05:42.040 --> 00:05:43.930
this is like gone from a lot of compute

00:05:43.930 --> 00:05:46.240
to like the biggest
infrastructure project in history.

00:05:46.240 --> 00:05:47.920
And out of that emerged Stargate,

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:48.920
Why call it Stargate?

00:05:50.020 --> 00:05:52.840
It began as a code name and
sometimes code name stick,

00:05:52.840 --> 00:05:54.070
But it means something, right?

00:05:54.070 --> 00:05:55.300
Oh,

00:05:55.300 --> 00:05:58.700
The design of one of
the very early layouts

00:05:58.700 --> 00:06:01.085
of a data center looked a
little bit like Stargate from

00:06:01.085 --> 00:06:02.810
the, from the show.

00:06:02.810 --> 00:06:05.300
How did you get to
talking with Masayoshi Son

00:06:05.300 --> 00:06:08.120
and Larry Ellison and how
did you all come together?

00:06:08.960 --> 00:06:10.880
I did two kind of long
trips around the world

00:06:10.880 --> 00:06:14.810
and a lot of it was to talk
to developers and governments,

00:06:14.810 --> 00:06:16.790
but a lot of it was
also to just really try

00:06:16.790 --> 00:06:20.420
to like get my head
around the supply chain.

00:06:20.420 --> 00:06:22.670
On one of those trips I met with Masa

00:06:22.670 --> 00:06:24.470
and we got to speaking about,
you know, what it would take

00:06:24.470 --> 00:06:26.030
to do compute at this kind of scale.

00:06:27.050 --> 00:06:29.570
Hi Masa. It's so nice to see you.

00:06:29.570 --> 00:06:30.890
What conversations did you have

00:06:30.890 --> 00:06:31.723
with Sam that led to Stargate?

00:06:31.723 --> 00:06:32.556
Well, we have a shared vision of

00:06:38.240 --> 00:06:42.770
AGI coming soon and we need compute

00:06:42.770 --> 00:06:44.120
Of all the bets you could make.

00:06:44.120 --> 00:06:46.280
Why this? Why Stargate?

00:06:46.280 --> 00:06:50.840
Well, I, I believe in
the vision that this AI

00:06:50.840 --> 00:06:54.500
the AGI will change the mankind's life

00:06:55.340 --> 00:06:57.050
in every aspect

00:06:57.050 --> 00:07:02.050
and we are lucky to see
this enormous revolution

00:07:02.330 --> 00:07:07.280
and I, I'd like to be part
of that and get excited.

00:07:07.280 --> 00:07:11.420
Last month I came to
celebrate your winning

00:07:11.420 --> 00:07:16.010
and promise that we will
invest $100 billion.

00:07:16.010 --> 00:07:19.370
And you told me, oh Masa go for 200.

00:07:21.710 --> 00:07:23.960
Now I came back with 500.

00:07:23.960 --> 00:07:25.190
Explain the math to us.

00:07:25.190 --> 00:07:28.310
How does it all add up
to needing $500 billion?

00:07:28.310 --> 00:07:30.440
Well, that covers the
capacity we think we need

00:07:30.440 --> 00:07:32.865
for the next few years given
our growth projections.

00:07:32.865 --> 00:07:35.420
The, the interesting question
is, if we had a, if we knew

00:07:35.420 --> 00:07:37.850
how to get a trillion dollars
right now, if we don't,

00:07:37.850 --> 00:07:39.710
would we be able to deploy

00:07:39.710 --> 00:07:41.330
that profitably in the next few years?

00:07:42.620 --> 00:07:43.940
And I'm not sure about that,

00:07:43.940 --> 00:07:45.530
but I feel confident we can like make

00:07:45.530 --> 00:07:46.730
500 billion of value back.

00:07:48.650 --> 00:07:50.270
Alright, so what are we seeing?

00:07:50.270 --> 00:07:51.770
There's many forklifts

00:07:51.770 --> 00:07:54.050
and there's many cranes,
there's many dump trucks,

00:07:54.050 --> 00:07:55.640
there's many excavators.

00:07:55.640 --> 00:07:57.560
New creatures emerge at every turn.

00:07:59.030 --> 00:08:00.770
Are most of the workers from Abilene?

00:08:00.770 --> 00:08:03.110
We're a very large
employer here in Abilene,

00:08:03.110 --> 00:08:06.170
but we, we have brought
in a lot of labor from

00:08:06.170 --> 00:08:08.330
outside the city and outside the state.

00:08:08.330 --> 00:08:10.730
We actually have workers
from seven different states.

00:08:12.020 --> 00:08:16.850
I've never built anything of this scale.

00:08:16.850 --> 00:08:19.520
It's one of the underappreciated aspects

00:08:19.520 --> 00:08:21.410
of AI is actually just the physical

00:08:21.410 --> 00:08:22.760
infrastructure that's needed.

00:08:24.500 --> 00:08:25.333
This is awesome. Awesome.

00:08:25.333 --> 00:08:26.166
I love it.

00:08:28.050 --> 00:08:29.330
We're building stuff. Yes.

00:08:29.330 --> 00:08:31.550
There's 155 vehicles

00:08:31.550 --> 00:08:34.460
that are moving dirt
moving earth right now.

00:08:34.460 --> 00:08:36.410
There's something so
satisfying about seeing

00:08:36.410 --> 00:08:38.060
lots of dirt being moved.

00:08:38.060 --> 00:08:42.380
Yeah, yeah, absolutely.
If you look at that crane,

00:08:42.380 --> 00:08:43.845
like this red crane

00:08:43.845 --> 00:08:45.530
That's a 600 ton crane.

00:08:46.880 --> 00:08:48.080
So, I have no like, how does

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:49.490
that compare to other cranes?

00:08:49.490 --> 00:08:50.930
It's, it can lift a lot.

00:08:50.930 --> 00:08:52.280
It can, it can lift a lot of weight.

00:08:52.280 --> 00:08:54.830
I mean 600 ton, that's like
a hundred elephants, right?

00:08:56.220 --> 00:08:57.780
This is actually
happening around the world.

00:08:57.780 --> 00:08:59.670
Data centers are being built in Malaysia

00:08:59.670 --> 00:09:01.685
and Japan and France.

00:09:01.685 --> 00:09:04.740
I, I think the demand
for compute infrastructure,

00:09:04.740 --> 00:09:07.620
it's not a US phenomenon,
it is a global phenomenon.

00:09:07.620 --> 00:09:10.080
A lot of countries had actually decided

00:09:10.080 --> 00:09:13.080
that data centers are, are
critical infrastructure

00:09:13.080 --> 00:09:14.610
that must be accelerated.

00:09:14.610 --> 00:09:16.560
So if, if hyperscalers
are going to Malaysia

00:09:16.560 --> 00:09:19.140
or Japan, is that competition for you?

00:09:19.140 --> 00:09:20.700
We don't really see it as competition.

00:09:20.700 --> 00:09:22.440
We, we kind of see it as, you know,

00:09:22.440 --> 00:09:24.930
just an overall growth of the sector.

00:09:24.930 --> 00:09:27.120
We think we have, you know, a
lot of unique ways of doing it

00:09:27.120 --> 00:09:28.980
and a lot of value to add
in the, in the process.

00:09:28.980 --> 00:09:30.690
But, you know, pretty just excited

00:09:30.690 --> 00:09:32.070
by everything happening in the space.

00:09:33.840 --> 00:09:36.180
Lochmiller's path to
leading the Stargate build has

00:09:36.180 --> 00:09:38.220
been circuitous.

00:09:38.220 --> 00:09:41.040
He's climbed five of the
so-called seven summits,

00:09:41.040 --> 00:09:43.200
the tallest mountain on each continent

00:09:43.200 --> 00:09:45.390
and worked in physics and finance.

00:09:45.390 --> 00:09:47.550
Tell me about your journey before Crusoe.

00:09:47.550 --> 00:09:50.730
You grew up in Denver,
you started out using AI

00:09:50.730 --> 00:09:52.440
as a trader on Wall Street.

00:09:52.440 --> 00:09:54.240
Yeah, we were big early adopters

00:09:54.240 --> 00:09:57.060
of deep learning using these
multi-layer neural networks

00:09:57.060 --> 00:10:01.080
to predict returns for certain securities.

00:10:01.080 --> 00:10:04.050
And, you know, we found
them to be fairly effective.

00:10:04.050 --> 00:10:05.070
I had high conviction

00:10:05.070 --> 00:10:06.480
that AI was gonna transform everything.

00:10:06.480 --> 00:10:10.050
It sort of always felt
like this, this meta science.

00:10:10.050 --> 00:10:13.500
Lochmiller eventually left
finance to get into crypto,

00:10:13.500 --> 00:10:16.350
not in the get rich quick
hyping meme coins way,

00:10:16.350 --> 00:10:19.830
but in the hundreds of computers
solving math problems way.

00:10:19.830 --> 00:10:23.070
His idea was to build Bitcoin
mining operations near oil

00:10:23.070 --> 00:10:24.510
rigs, taking advantage

00:10:24.510 --> 00:10:27.210
of a quirk in the oil drilling process.

00:10:27.210 --> 00:10:29.970
When an oil company drills for oil, one

00:10:29.970 --> 00:10:33.270
of the associated byproducts
of that is natural gas.

00:10:33.270 --> 00:10:35.880
And when they don't have
access to a pipeline, all

00:10:35.880 --> 00:10:38.670
of this associated gas is
just being burned off on site.

00:10:38.670 --> 00:10:41.130
And so we had this concept
that instead of trying to bring

00:10:41.130 --> 00:10:43.560
that gas to a market
where you can sell it,

00:10:43.560 --> 00:10:45.390
we could bring a market to the gas.

00:10:45.390 --> 00:10:48.180
We could build these mobile
and modular data centers

00:10:48.180 --> 00:10:50.340
and bring them directly to the wellhead

00:10:50.340 --> 00:10:52.950
and then use that power
to power the data center.

00:10:52.950 --> 00:10:56.520
It was a good idea
with unfortunate timing.

00:10:56.520 --> 00:10:58.140
The crypto market crashed.

00:10:58.140 --> 00:11:00.270
You then went from bitcoin mining to AI.

00:11:00.270 --> 00:11:03.000
It almost sounds like going
from one hype cycle to another.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:05.970
Yeah, it may seem like
that from the outside,

00:11:05.970 --> 00:11:10.410
but I, I'll say that, you
know, from very early on we,

00:11:10.410 --> 00:11:13.590
we had planned to build an
AI infrastructure business.

00:11:13.590 --> 00:11:14.940
So what do Bitcoin mining

00:11:14.940 --> 00:11:17.160
and AI data centers have in common?

00:11:17.160 --> 00:11:18.300
Number one, they, they both

00:11:18.300 --> 00:11:19.620
consume a tremendous amount of energy.

00:11:20.820 --> 00:11:23.340
Number two, they're both

00:11:23.340 --> 00:11:26.370
more location agnostic than
traditional data centers.

00:11:27.330 --> 00:11:30.750
Northern Virginia is
largely perceived to be sort

00:11:30.750 --> 00:11:33.690
of the center of the world
for data centers today.

00:11:33.690 --> 00:11:35.520
That's data center 1.0. Right?

00:11:35.520 --> 00:11:36.600
That's data center 1.0.

00:11:37.920 --> 00:11:40.710
Virginia's data center alley
is where the first generation

00:11:40.710 --> 00:11:42.540
of cloud computing was built close

00:11:42.540 --> 00:11:43.740
to the government agencies

00:11:43.740 --> 00:11:45.450
that created the original internet.

00:11:46.380 --> 00:11:50.130
Those data centers are full
of CPUs, basic computer chips

00:11:50.130 --> 00:11:53.080
that power everyday things
like social media streaming.

00:11:53.080 --> 00:11:56.050
And the cloud. Stargate,
on the other hand, is part

00:11:56.050 --> 00:11:59.230
of a new era of data centers full of GPUs.

00:11:59.230 --> 00:12:01.750
The special advanced
chips needed to power AI

